\title{steinsampling: Stein tests and Stein sampling tools}
\description{
Tools for score-based goodness-of-fit testing and Stein-based sampling in R.
The package provides KSD and FSSD tests, Stein thinning, Stein Points,
SP-MCMC, SVGD, and reusable Stein kernel objects.
}
\details{
Most functions in this package work with a score function. For a target
density \code{p(x)}, the score is the gradient of the log density,
\deqn{s_p(x) = \nabla_x \log p(x).}
This means many tests and samplers can be used without knowing the
normalizing constant of \code{p(x)}.

The main testing functions are \code{\link[=ksd_u_test]{ksd_u_test()}}, \code{\link[=ksd_v_test]{ksd_v_test()}}, and
\code{\link[=fssd_test]{fssd_test()}}. The main sampling, compression, and point-construction
functions are \code{\link[=stein_thinning]{stein_thinning()}}, \code{\link[=stein_points]{stein_points()}}, \code{\link[=sp_mcmc]{sp_mcmc()}}, and
\code{\link[=svgd]{svgd()}}. The helper \code{\link[=stein_kernel]{stein_kernel()}} creates the built-in kernels used by
these methods, and the Gaussian mixture helpers such as \code{\link[=gmm]{gmm()}} and
\code{\link[=scorefunctiongmm]{scorefunctiongmm()}} are included for small simulations and examples.

The public API is organized in layers. The top layer runs complete methods:
\code{\link[=ksd_u_test]{ksd_u_test()}}, \code{\link[=ksd_v_test]{ksd_v_test()}}, \code{\link[=fssd_test]{fssd_test()}}, \code{\link[=stein_thinning]{stein_thinning()}},
\code{\link[=stein_points]{stein_points()}}, \code{\link[=sp_mcmc]{sp_mcmc()}}, and \code{\link[=svgd]{svgd()}}. The next layer exposes the
reusable numerical pieces used by those methods, such as
\code{\link[=stein_kernel_matrix]{stein_kernel_matrix()}}, \code{\link[=ksd_uq_matrix]{ksd_uq_matrix()}}, \code{\link[=ksd_u_statistic]{ksd_u_statistic()}},
\code{\link[=ksd_u_bootstrap]{ksd_u_bootstrap()}}, \code{\link[=ksd_vq_matrix]{ksd_vq_matrix()}}, \code{\link[=ksd_v_statistic]{ksd_v_statistic()}},
\code{\link[=ksd_v_bootstrap]{ksd_v_bootstrap()}}, \code{\link[=compute_tau]{compute_tau()}}, \code{\link[=compute_fssd_unbiased_stat]{compute_fssd_unbiased_stat()}}, and
\code{\link[=compute_fssd_null_pvalue]{compute_fssd_null_pvalue()}}. These lower-level functions are exported so a
user can inspect intermediate matrices, reuse the same bootstrap weights, or
reproduce a paper calculation one step at a time.

The main testing path is top-down. Start with \code{\link[=ksd_u_test]{ksd_u_test()}} for the Liu,
Lee, and Jordan independent-sample KSD test, \code{\link[=ksd_v_test]{ksd_v_test()}} for the
Chwialkowski et al. V-statistic and wild-bootstrap version, or \code{\link[=fssd_test]{fssd_test()}}
for a finite-feature Stein test. Moving down from \code{\link[=ksd_u_test]{ksd_u_test()}} gives
\code{\link[=ksd_uq_matrix]{ksd_uq_matrix()}} for the Stein-kernel matrix, \code{\link[=ksd_u_statistic]{ksd_u_statistic()}} for the
off-diagonal U-statistic, and \code{\link[=ksd_u_bootstrap]{ksd_u_bootstrap()}} for the centered
multinomial bootstrap. Moving sideways to \code{\link[=ksd_v_test]{ksd_v_test()}} keeps the same
sample, score function, and kernel layer, but changes the matrix compression
to include the diagonal and changes the bootstrap weights to Rademacher or
Markov signs. Moving sideways to \code{\link[=fssd_test]{fssd_test()}} keeps the same score-function
idea but replaces the full pairwise matrix by \code{\link[=compute_tau]{compute_tau()}}, a finite set
of Stein features evaluated at test locations.

The sampling, compression, and point-construction path uses the same
Stein-kernel layer in different ways. \code{\link[=stein_thinning]{stein_thinning()}} is a compression
method: it starts from an existing sample matrix, usually an MCMC output, and
returns row indices for a smaller empirical measure. \code{\link[=stein_points]{stein_points()}} is a
point-construction method: it searches over continuous candidates using an
optimizer such as \code{\link[=fmin_grid]{fmin_grid()}}, \code{\link[=fmin_mc]{fmin_mc()}}, or \code{\link[=fmin_nm]{fmin_nm()}}. \code{\link[=sp_mcmc]{sp_mcmc()}} is a
Stein Points variant that uses short MCMC paths as finite candidate sets for
constructing new support points. \code{\link[=svgd]{svgd()}} and \code{\link[=update_svgd]{update_svgd()}} move all
particles by a deterministic transport update rather than compressing an
existing sample or selecting a point sequence.

Kernel functions form a separate layer. \code{\link[=stein_kernel]{stein_kernel()}} and
\code{\link[=custom_stein_kernel]{custom_stein_kernel()}} create kernel objects. The generic functions
\code{\link[=eval_kernel]{eval_kernel()}}, \code{\link[=grad_x_kernel]{grad_x_kernel()}}, \code{\link[=trace_mixed_kernel]{trace_mixed_kernel()}},
\code{\link[=cross_kernel]{cross_kernel()}}, and \code{\link[=grad_theta_v_kernel]{grad_theta_v_kernel()}} expose the pieces needed to
assemble the scalar Stein kernel \code{k0} or the finite-location FSSD features.
Most users call the top-level algorithms and never call these generics
directly; they are public because custom kernels and diagnostic checks need
the same interface as the built-in kernels.

The Gaussian mixture helpers form an example-model layer. \code{\link[=gmm]{gmm()}} creates a
model, \code{\link[=rgmm]{rgmm()}} simulates from it, \code{\link[=likelihoodgmm]{likelihoodgmm()}},
\code{\link[=posteriorgmm]{posteriorgmm()}}, and \code{\link[=scorefunctiongmm]{scorefunctiongmm()}} evaluate density-related
quantities, and \code{\link[=get_score_evaluator]{get_score_evaluator()}} turns a fixed mixture into the
\verb{function(X)} score callback expected by the Stein routines.
